<subSubSection id="C304FCE6761DFFDB69901E2F1668FE42" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BA1AF6D761DFFDB69901E2F1668FE42" blockId="18.[151,1437,151,487]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis id="B96A737F761DFFDB69901E2F135DFEE9" bold="true" box="[197,320,306,332]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Remarks:</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EF8FD29C761DFFDB681D1E2F1092FEE9" author="Painter" box="[328,655,306,332]" pageId="18" pageNumber="49" refString="Painter, R. H. &amp; E. M. Painter. (1962) Notes on and redescriptions of types of North American Bombyliidae (Diptera) in European Museums. Journal of the Kansas Entomological Society, 35, 2 - 164." type="journal article" year="1962">
Painter &amp; Painter (
<number id="3DD6BD4A761DFFDB6B711E2F107EFEE9" box="[548,611,306,332]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="1962.0">1962</number>
: 
<number id="3DD6BD4A761DFFDB6B331E2F109BFEE9" box="[614,646,306,332]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="96.0">96</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
proposed a synonymy between 
<taxonomicName id="4C1ED4EE761DFFDB6D5D1E2F1686FEEE" box="[1032,1179,306,331]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Hemipenthes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chimaera">
<emphasis id="B96A737F761DFFDB6D5D1E2F1686FEEE" box="[1032,1179,306,331]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">H. chimaera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C1ED4EE761DFFDB6D811E2F1772FEEE" box="[1236,1391,306,331]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Hemipenthes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="comanche">
<emphasis id="B96A737F761DFFDB6D811E2F1772FEEE" box="[1236,1391,306,331]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">H. comanche</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but these two species can be distinguished by the tomentum in fifth and sixth abdominal tergites being black in 
<taxonomicName id="4C1ED4EE761DFFDB6C2A1E4412E5FE3C" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Hemipenthes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chimera">
<emphasis id="B96A737F761DFFDB6C2A1E4412E5FE3C" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">H. chimera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and white in 
<taxonomicName id="4C1ED4EE761DFFDB68C91E9D1024FE3C" box="[412,569,384,409]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Hemipenthes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="comanche">
<emphasis id="B96A737F761DFFDB68C91E9D1024FE3C" box="[412,569,384,409]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">H. comanche</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName id="4C1ED4EE761DFFDB6B1C1E9D1141FE3C" box="[585,860,384,409]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Hemipenthes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chimaera">
<emphasis id="B96A737F761DFFDB6B1C1E9D1141FE3C" box="[585,860,384,409]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Hemipenthes chimaera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="4C1ED4EE761DFFDB6D3D1E9D171FFE3C" box="[1128,1282,384,409]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Hemipenthes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bigradata">
<emphasis id="B96A737F761DFFDB6D3D1E9D171FFE3C" box="[1128,1282,384,409]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">H. bigradata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the black pile on mesopleuron. The genitalia of this species is rare by not having a ventral extension in epiphallus, a character shared only with 
<taxonomicName id="4C1ED4EE761DFFDB68811ED0102AFE43" box="[468,567,461,486]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Hemipenthes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albus">
<emphasis id="B96A737F761DFFDB68811ED0102AFE43" box="[468,567,461,486]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">H. albus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; and the epiphallus being slender in lateral view.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
